The paper deals with optimization of distance between buildings on a 2-dimensional integer grid, which falls under computational geometry (cs.CG). The algorithmic approach used to compute optimal n-towns involves dynamic programming and matrix multiplication, which are common techniques in data structures (cs.DS) and numerical analysis (cs.NA). The problem of minimizing pairwise distances can also be viewed as a combinatorial optimization problem (cs.DM). Finally, the practical applications of the algorithm in computing optimal solutions for n up to 80 suggest that it may be relevant to scientific computing (cs.SI).
